text: The ﬁrst time I heard about the Nozoe Autograph Books[1–3] was at the ICCEOCA-8 / NICCEOCA-4 (The 8th Interna- tional Conference on Cutting-Edge Organic Chemistry in Asia / The 4th New Phase International Conference on Cutting- Edge Organic Chemistry in Asia) meeting in Osaka, Japan by no other than Eva Wille.[4] Professor Keisuke Suzuki had intro- duced me to her at this same conference, by pointing out that we were namesakes. I was immediately captivated by Professor Nozoe and the many autographs he collected. Flipping through the pages, I found elaborate drawings, schemes, cartoons, Chem. Note from the Editor: Science, collegiality, travel without borders. Big smiles and warmth. Eternally youthful vigor. When I think of Tetsuo Nozoe, these are the images that immediately come to mind. When I think of the Nozoe Autograph Books, I also think of time. For 40 years, Nozoe carried with him his autograph books and collected his treasures which The Chemical Record is now publishing. Vladimir Prelog signed ﬁrst when he was 47 and signed last when he was almost 80. Derek Barton signed ﬁrst when he was 35 and signed last when he was almost 70. Time! I was fascinated by Eva Wille’s recommendation that we publish an essay by Eva-Maria Tanzer, a young organic chemist with already a lifetime’s experience in exploring chemical research in laboratories around the world. Tanzer brings to us a charming, even innocent perspective that embraces so much of Tetsuo Nozoe’s ideals. We are privileged to include Tanzer’s vision and her experiences in the collection of essays that accompany the Nozoe Autograph Books. Our contributors range in age and experiences, from the youthful Tanzer to the more mature (including myself!) as do the signatories in the autograph books. Tetsuo Nozoe would have beamed! poems and greetings from all over the world and not just chemists but all sorts of people he met during his travels. What fascinated me the most was imagining the circum- stances under which these autographs came to existence and what special open and friendly personality it took to ask all these people to leave a memento. I was especially happy to see that I myself crossed paths with some of these people, which established a sense of connection. The kind of autographs that these people left in his book gave me a better sense of who Professor Nozoe was. Furthermore, reading about Professor DOI: 10.1002/tcr.201402055 Guest Editor University of Richmond Richmond, Virginia 23173, USA E-mail: jseeman@richmond.edu Nozoe’s life and his travels made me take a step back and think about my own adventures as a young chemist and see some similarities. Professor Nozoe started his autograph books with his international travels in 1953.

Exactly 50 years later, in 2003, I embarked on my great science adventure starting with the studies of Chemistry at the Julius-Maximilians University in Würzburg, Germany. It soon became clear to me that my curiosity did not stop with what was going on in the laboratories of my professors in Würzburg, but that I wanted to go and see how things were done at other places around the globe. Of course, I was fascinated by differ- ent cultures and happy to study a new language or two, but most of all I was anxious to learn how chemistry was perceived, taught and done in laboratories around the world. With the enthusiastic invitation and encouragement of Dr. Wille and the Guest Editor of the Nozoe Autograph Book project, Jeffrey I. Seeman, I am writing this essay to share my experiences in studying chemistry on three continents and four countries in my very short career so far as a chemist. My love of travel and enjoyment of people remind me of those same characteristics of the great Tetsuo Nozoe. Living the American Dream

After passing my pre-diploma studies at the Julius-Maximilians University in Würzburg in 2005 at the age of 21, I decided to start looking for a laboratory position at one of the famous American universities that would accept a master student for a six month research internship. I was already entertaining the idea of pursuing my PhD abroad. I had a pretty good idea of what research might be like in Europe, thanks to talking with multiple postdoctoral fellows during my studies. However, I was not fully aware how the American system compared and was interested to discover for myself. So instead of going ERASMUS (European Community Action Scheme for the Mobility of University Students = European Union student exchange program) I decided to organize everything myself and go to the United States. Since this research stay was not part of my diploma curriculum, and therefore deemed unnecessary by the faculty of my undergraduate school, the best thing I could do was to take a vacation semester and ﬁt the research intern- ship into this time frame, giving me a total of six months to study abroad. Surprisingly, organizing it was not a very straightforward endeavor. Funding agencies in Germany kept telling me that for a chemist it was not essential to go abroad before pursuing either a PhD or a postdoctoral stay (I beg to differ). Ironically, they would have happily provided scholar- ships if I wanted to dance on Broadway.[5] Furthermore, some of the professors at my university did not look too fondly at the idea of me taking a vacation semester to work at another support. They university without receiving any ﬁnancial T H E C H E M I C A L R E C O R D Chem. Rec. 2014, 14, 709–725 © 2014 The Chemical Society of Japan and Wiley-VCH, Weinheim

thought that ﬁnishing the studies faster and not taking this six month detour would be more beneﬁcial to me in the long run. However, after explaining my motives to Professor Gerhard Bringmann he kindly agreed to support me (e.g., providing letters of recommendation, functioning as a contact person etc.) with my multinational academic plans. I started perusing the internet for a group I would be interested in working for and found the laboratory of Professor Rick L. Danheiser at MIT.

The Danheiser group researches a variety of topics that caught my attention. Along with developing novel methodolo- gies for cycloadditions and annulations (e.g. the Danheiser benzannulation) to be employed in the total synthesis of bio- logically active compounds, green chemistry was also on the agenda. Another of my criteria was a small to midsize group, because I ﬁgured that in this kind of layout it would be easier to ﬁnd out about everyone’s projects and have the best learning experience possible. Of course, it did not hurt that Professor Danheiser had won numerous awards for being an outstanding teacher and that his group was situated in one of the most prestigious schools when it comes to studying chemistry in all of the United States. I guess the fact that I would be living in Boston (Cambridge) was the icing on the cake. Soon after I had identiﬁed my desired target, the next difﬁculty became appar- ent. After having sent all my application materials to the States, I got a very polite e-mail from Prof. Danheiser to say that he was very sorry that there was no position for me in his lab. I still remember reading his reply and getting so upset because this was the science I wanted to do, and that there must be a possibility to somehow do it. So here is the best example of ﬁghting for your dreams: I replied to this e-mail, making it abundantly clear that he was my ﬁrst choice for a research stay, and that I would give anything for a chance to work in his lab, even if it was just for a couple of weeks instead of months—and it paid off. My tenacity, dedication and passion for his chem- istry swayed Prof. Danheiser, and an invitation to join his group followed.

And that is how I started my ﬁrst big science adventure (the full six months!) at the Massachusetts Institute of Tech- nology in Boston, Massachusetts, USA in April of 2007, after having just completed my graduate work (I only had to take the oral diploma examination and write my diploma thesis to become Dipl. Chem. upon my return to Germany). This was the ﬁrst time for me working by myself in an organic chemistry lab, having my own project and no 100% set instructions. Admittedly I was scared, but my lab mates turned out to be amazing, as was Prof. Danheiser (Figure 1). I did not just have one teacher or mentor, but I had a whole lab full of them—everybody took time and effort to explain their projects to me, to show me proper laboratory techniques, and to quiz me on reaction mechanisms. Undeni- ably, at the beginning it was quite a challenge to discuss all Fig. 1. The Danheiser group in spring of 2007. From left to right: Jennie Fong, Xiao-Yin Mak, myself, Tammy Lam, Kevin Maloney, Julia Robinson, Wes Austin, Mandeep Virdi, Shaun Fontaine. science in English and be sure that I had understood correctly what was asked of me, but luckily chemical formulas and reaction schemes are not language-dependent! As it turned out, ﬁnding an apartment in Cambridge was almost as difﬁcult as my ﬁrst couple of ﬂash-column chroma- tography separations. While apartment hunting I identiﬁed the following problems: (1) shady neighborhoods, (2) vermin infestation (if there are multiple posters around the house giving you the number of the nearest exterminator, it is not a strong sell), (3) too pricey, (4) not available for rent for such a short timeframe and last but not least (5) unfurnished. So in my desperation I had committed to be a boarder at a private apartment until I could ﬁnd my own place. Of course as luck has it, within days of moving into my boarding room I was able to sign the lease for my own accommodations, to be moved in a couple of days later.

To my dismay, the man who had rented me the boarding room insisted on me paying three months of rent to him before letting me go—I was devastated (as a student money is kind of hard to come by). Arriving at work that day I must have looked very miserable, because one of the PhD students, Wes Austin, approached me right away and asked what was going on. In tears I told him everything. That same day, I experienced for the ﬁrst time of many more to come, that a research laboratory is more than just a couple of people being interested in science, it is a research family. Wes called his wife, a lawyer, who had told him exactly what to do and say to get me out of this wretched situation. That night Wes accompanied me to the apartment complex, and thanks to his presence and valid arguments I was moved out of this displeasing leaving situation in no time with the full refund of my money. So for the next three nights I slept on the couch of my lab mate whom I had known for a total of 2 weeks, feeling right at home.

During my six months at MIT, I discovered not only my love for organic synthesis but my ﬁrst science family, people who were just as passionate about chemistry as I was, curious about my background and my support system in the time of need. I was not just a visitor; I was part of something bigger, struggling with experiments and discussing all of the problems and setbacks, celebrating the successful completion of a syn- thesis that was the uniting factor (Figure 2). So when I returned to Germany in October of 2007, I did so with a heavy heart. Luckily for me the internet (face- book, Skype etc.) made it extremely easy to keep in touch, and so I would call my former bench partner, Jennie Fong, at least once a week to hear about the lab and her scientiﬁc progress. Meanwhile, back at the Julius-Maximilians University in Würzburg, Germany, I started to work on my diploma thesisunder the supervision of Professors Bringmann and Breuning (Figure 4). Fig. 4. The Breuning group in March of 2009 during our trip to the crag. Did I mention, I am really afraid of heights! During my time at MIT, I was part of the team that worked on a practical total synthesis of Glycinoeclepin A (Figure 3). This particular compound is a kairomon (= allelochemical) that stimulates the hatching of the larvae of the soybean cyst nematode. There is a high demand for a non-toxic pest control against this plant parasite, since nematodes destroy ca. $100 billion in crops worldwide per year. Scheme 1. I chose this group, because during my research stay I had realized two things: (1) I am really passionate about organic chemistry and this is what I want to do with my life and (2) stereochemistry is important and learning to control it in reac- tions is essential. So working with chiral auxiliaries to make α-amino acids or α-hydroxy esters seemed to be a good ﬁrst step towards fulﬁlling both of these requirements. Shaped by my ﬁrst great exchange at MIT, I also acted as an ambassador for studying abroad. I encourage students who are interested in this kind of foreign exchange experience to research the possibilities, informing them about what actions I had taken to make my research stay a reality and the factors to consider in planning out such a research stay, e.g., the ideal time to go, where to go and interested topics of study etc. On another note, my German science family (the Breuning group) turned out to be just as compassionate and interested as my American one (the Danheiser group). Even though I was pretty self-sufﬁcient when it came to laboratory work, owing to my independent research at MIT, I still had to learn a lot when it The title of my diploma thesis was “Multi Heteroatom Cope-Rearrangements (MHACR) of Oxazoline-N-Ox- ides—Research into Broadening the Scope and Applicability of this Method”.[7] The objective of my research work was to gain access to enantiomerically pure α-amino acids or α-hydroxy esters in a one-pot procedure from various ortho the multi heteroatom the synthesis Cope rearrangement as the key step of (Scheme 1). The application of this method in the synthesis of methylesters of un/naturally occurring α-hydroxy acids such as l-phenyllactic acid proved to be very successful and presents a novel way for the preparation of these important synthetic building blocks. We were also able to prove that it is possible to extend the method to various other electrophiles; however, further optimization was required to establish this as a competitive methodology next to already existing procedures.

came to puzzling out what undesired pathway a reaction had taken or how to cope with the constant failure we experience in every day lab life. (Let us be honest, as a scientist in lab we have more of the cuss word moments than the eureka moments.) But thanks to the PhD students in my German group and their support, I learned that “it is not over until it’s over” and that no matter how frustrating the science might be at times (e.g., experiments that do not work as expected, results that are just incomprehensible, or compounds that are just not stable to any form of analysis, the list of what can go wrong goes on and on) you can rely on your lab mates to cheer you up and get you going again. However, it is not just about receiving this support; it is just as much about giving it back. I would make sure to do my very best to keep my fellow co-workers happy and motivated. This was fairly easy for me since I was always curious to learn what my lab mates were working on and engaging them in discussions about their science. Due to that fact, I always knew when someone was in need of a strong coffee or a big piece of chocolate cake and a hug. Professor Danheiser once said that my enthusiasm for organic chemistry is infectious; I guess it helps when you love what you do.

Even though I loved my new group back home, my curi- osity had been sparked by my time abroad and it was clear to me from the start that my PhD thesis had to take me some- where else entirely. The University of Würzburg was a wonder- ful place for getting my Diploma, but I was now familiar with all the groups at the university and the research they were doing. So, if MIT had taught me anything (other than a whole lot of amazing chemistry), it was that pushing the boundaries of your comfort zone, going to new places and learning about novel things is what inspires you and helps you grow profes- sionally and personally. I know that for most people it is an odd thing to want to change countries and places so much, because what we know and what is familiar is what makes us feel safe. The unknown, the different language, foreign food, customs in other places is what makes us curious, but also what scares us a little if we have to stay longer than just a couple of days or weeks for a vacation. But I guess for me exploring my own boundaries and pushing out of my comfort zone showed me a different side of myself every time. I love getting to know new people and hearing their take on life and science. It makes me rethink and adjust what I know and what I have learnt—and it inspires my love for chemistry. So, unsurprisingly, when it was time to apply for PhD positions my chemistry family came once again into play. When Jennie Fong (my former bench partner from MIT) decided to visit me in Germany, we took this opportunity to also visit Xiao Yin-Mak (another former PhD of the Danheiser group), who was then a postdoctoral fellow at the ETH in Zürich, Switzerland (Figure 5). During this trip to Zürich, with the insights and knowledge of my science family, I made the decision to apply to a young Chem. Professor at ETH for my PhD thesis. After reading all my praise for MIT, the attentive reader might wonder why not go back there, and I can give you the rational reason that inﬂuenced this choice: time. MIT would have required me to stay for ﬁve years in order to earn a PhD degree, since I would have to retake the master courses there (of course that was before the introduction of the Bachelor’s and Master’s degrees into the German system, so it might be different today). However, my previous experi- ences helped me identify exactly what I wanted for my ideal PhD destination: a well-equipped school with an excellent reputa- tion. This would place me in a competitive work environment providing me with the means to perform cutting edge science and, therefore, pushing me to be the best I can be. Of course, great science can be done anywhere, but with the necessary resources a lot more possibilities can open up. So, why not take advantage of this opportunity? Also, regarding the reason for applying to a young professor, apart from his fascinating research ideas, I guess I wanted to be part of something that was growing and developing before my very eyes. To my great delight, I was invited to interview for my desired PhD position with Professor Ryan Gilmour. At this time his group only consisted of two Swiss PhD students, who I really knocked over with my very direct German ways (I told one of his students he was not very charming, which in turn led to years of amusing anecdotes in our group). Nevertheless, I was hired and started working in the Gilmour group on July 1, 2009, which incidentally was also the day of the laboratory’s ﬁrst group trip (Figure 6)—what better way to start your new work experience. These next three years at ETH as part of the Gilmour group were life shaping. I guess one can say that doing a PhD is not a job, rather it is a calling and a lesson for life. I am entirely grateful to Professor Gilmour for pushing me and “my Fig. 5. From left to right: myself, Xiao Yin-Mak and Jennie Fong at Lake Zürich in summer of 2008.

From left to right: Christof Sparr, Julia Bachmann, Professor Ryan Gilmour, myself, Christoph Bucher, Susann Paul, Georg Geisberger. buttons”, because he saw potential at a time when I saw only doubt. I realized myself how much I had grown as a scientist when I started writing up my PhD thesis. I could see a very clear development from where I took over a project to making it my project. When I started my PhD I was conﬁdent in my laboratory skills, but I was hesitant to put forward my own ideas or tell my boss when I thought that his suggestions might not work so well in a particular case. By the end of the ﬁrst year Fig. 7. Utilizing the ﬂuorine gauche effect in the design of small molecul organocatalysts. T H E C H E M I C A L R E C O R D Chem. By the end of the three years I was eager to put forward ideas and suggestions and ready to battle it out with Prof. Gilmour on the white board.

The aim of my doctoral thesis (“The Fluorine Gauche Effect—Acyclic Conformational Control in Organocatalyst Design”)[9] was to design small molecule catalysts that are conformationally dynamic and, thus, can undergo confor- mational changes triggered by substrate binding. This can be achieved by strategically embedding a β-ﬂuoroamine deriva- tive in the catalyst structure[10] and in doing so exploit the gauche conformational preference[11] of this moiety when condensed with an α,β-unsaturated aldehyde (Figure 7). Introducing additional structural features leading to stabi- lizing (e.g. π-stacking or C-H-π interactions) or destabilizing interactions helps discriminate between the two possible gauche conformations of the β-ﬂuoroiminium salt. This results in the possibility to predictably position substituents attached to the ﬂuorine-bearing carbon in an area of molecu- lar space and, in the case of enantioselective organocatalysis, exploit them as shielding groups to discriminate between one of two faces of a planar electrophile. The β-ﬂuoroamine (S)-2-(ﬂuorodiphenylmethyl)-pyrrolidine is an effective as catalyst well as the aziridation[13] of α,β-unsaturated aldehydes (Figure 7, middle). A process of editing has revealed that the efﬁciency of this catalyst is due to the Chem. Rec. 2014, 14, 709–725 © 2014 The Chemical Society of Japan and Wiley-VCH, Weinheim the (ﬂuorodiphenyl)methyl epoxidation and aziridation of challenging cyclic α,β- disubstituted, β,β-disubstituted and α,β,β-trisubstituted enals catalysed by (S)-2-(ﬂuorodiphenylmethyl)-pyrrolidine proceeded with excellent levels of enantiocontrol (up to 99% ee).[13,14]

Furthermore, we were able to extend this principal to chiral DMAP analogues, showing that by invoking the ﬂuorine gauche effect we could predictably control molecular space, by hindering rotation around the only rotatable sp3- sp3 bond.[15] This design approach was veriﬁed by X-ray analysis as well as computational methods, where a clear preference for the gauche conformation (φNCCF ≈ 60°) was apparent. With the goal of exploiting the similar ﬂuorine- ammonium ion gauche effect, a conﬁgurationally deﬁned ﬂuorine was installed at the C9 carbinol center of cinchona alkaloids (Figure 7, right).[16,17] This class of ligands has found widespread application as phase transfer catalysts. However, the C9 position functions as a molecular hinge with internal rotations around the C8-C9 (τ1) and C9-C4′ (τ2) bonds, giving rise to four low energy conformers. From the perspective of designing new catalysts with improved performance, a way to control this internal rotation is desir- able. The ﬂuorine-ammonium gauche effect encodes for two out of the four possible conformers by controlling the rota- tion around C8-C9, thereby partially solving the problem of conformational dynamics. The merit of this approach was displayed in the application of this novel class of chiral, ﬂuorinated cinchonium salts for the enantioselective, elec- trophilic ﬂuorination of β-ketoesters (up to 81% ee).[17] Furthermore, X-ray crystallography and solution phase con- formational analysis were successfully undertaken to gain insight into the catalysts mode of enantioinduction.[17] Fig. 8. Also, working in a newly established laboratory makes for a very special atmosphere and some especially close bonding. A few of my best memories come from our annual group trips (I guess it is hard to forget your Professor riding on a pony or almost capsizing a canoe with your terriﬁed lab partner inside) (Figure 8). I was also very eager to pass on the support I had felt and received during my earlier studies in the States and Germany. I must have been pretty successful with that approach, since Professor Gilmour once called me “the social glue of the lab”, the one that always pounces on every chance to interact with the new group members and makes them feel welcomed. Furthermore, I got to teach multiple lab courses and also some seminars to undergraduate students. My knack for orga- nizing things, if I may be a bit immodest, came very handy and I was happy to see that my enthusiasm for organic chemistry seemed to be infectious to some students. Not only was I able to work on amazing chemical research, but I got to do it in a building full of organic chemical legends (also the oldest post- doctoral fellows found in the world[18]), some of whom, by the way, also signed Professor Nozoe’s autograph books (Figure 9). This was intimidating and inspiring all at the same time. I think meeting your heroes in real life always is. What impressed me the most is that the passion for chemistry is still so strong in these great men. They love to discuss chemistry with stu- dents and share their wisdom and experiences (we got to see lots of marvelous photographs of Professor Prelog and Wood- ward, which were accompanied by funny anecdotes). And despite the fact that you ﬁnd them in every chemistry book their door is always open to students (and yes of course while conversing with them, one is always scared of saying something stupid). While other people cannot wait to retire, Professor Jack Dunitz is still coming to work every day and he just turned 91. If this is not inspiring, I do not know what is. Also he gives

excellent advice on contemporary literature. I had the great pleasure of interacting with Professor Dieter Seebach on the occasions of the Gilmour group Christmas parties; these were always educational and fun conversations not just about science, but also about winery and his many travels abroad. I count myself very fortunate to have met and talked to these four chemical giants—idols to live up to. Another important thing ETH provided was interna- tionality, not surprisingly for a Swiss educational institution of great renown; there were PhD students and postdoctoral fellows from not only Switzerland and Germany, but from all over Europe, Asia and North America. No wonder I kept running into familiar faces and meeting old acquaintances importantly, due to again at the everybody brought something else to the table to learn from and to discuss. Contrary to what some may believe, the German-speaking part of Switzerland is quite different from Germany. Next to having its own unique dialect and mentality, their trains actu- ally arrive on time while our trains are just presumed to be punctual. Even though I was not able to master the Swiss German dialect (when your pronunciation of (kitchen cabinet) to pronounced Chuchichäschtli laughter in the lab, you admit defeat after a while), the passion for chemistry was again the uniting factor. So it did not take very long to feel right at home in Zürich and in Switzerland. During my time at ETH we also had a guest lecture by no other than Prof. Keisuke Suzuki from the Tokyo Institute of Tech- nology in Japan, a talk that quite captivated my interest. Fig. 9. So two years later when I decided that Japan would be the next destination of my scientiﬁc travels, Prof. Suzuki came to mind. More importantly, my vastly expanded science family encouraged me again to take this step out of my comfort zone. In spring of 2012, I met Prof. Danheiser at the American Chemical Society meeting in San Diego and told him about my postdoctoral plans. I also met many other friends from my time at MIT (Figure 10). After having studied in Germany, the United States and Switzerland one of the other big chemistry hubs that was left to explore was Japan. Of course for my postdoctoral stay I wanted to branch out again and also broaden my chemical horizon by venturing into the ﬁeld of Fig. 11. At my PhD Apero, after successfully defending my PhD thesis, wearing the hat my group mates had made for me. total and glycosylation chemistry. Professor Danheiser has been a frequent guest lecturer in Japan and therefore also knew Professor Suzuki very well, so I was curious to hear his opinion for my plans. To my great delight, he was extremely supportive and encouraged me to contact Prof. Suzuki right away.

studying with Professor Suzuki was cemented when my PhD advisor, together with Professor Seebach, supported my application. So again a couple of obstacles had to be overcome, like getting accepted by the Suzuki-Ohmori laboratory, securing funding for my research plan and graduating from ETH. I was taking this one step at a time, checking things off of my to-do list. Consequently on December 12, 2012, I was able to tick off the last item on my list, the successful defense of my thesis (Figure 11). I guess this could be described as one of the best days of my life, the sense of accomplishment when your lab mates put their hand made PhD hat on your head and having your family and friends there with you. It was wonderful to see how many people I met during my time at ETH and the way we had all helped and inﬂuenced one another (borrowing chemicals from each other’s labs, equipment, pep talks, etc.). Thus, saying good-bye to this wonderful place that I called home for three and a half years was far from easy—but again some ties once formed hold strong. A Brief Layover in Germany Due to the restrictions of the JSPS (Japanese Society for the Promotion of Science), I could not start my fellowship in Japan before the beginning of April 2013. Instead of waiting idly at home, I made my way up to the Westfälische Wilhelms- Chem. Universität Münster (Figure 12), where Prof. Gilmour had moved to in September of 2012, three months prior to my defense (the group of Prof. Togni was so kind to grant me a mini-sabbatical during my thesis writing process at ETH). During this time I was able to help with the set-up of laboratories and eagerly getting to know the new members of the Gilmour group. By a remarkable and happy coincidence, I had my laboratory safety instructions together with a Japanese exchange student Tomohiro Yasukawa the ﬁrst day of my stay in Münster. This same student I would meet again at the Mukaiyama Aldol Reaction 40th Anniversary Symposium almost eight months later in Tokyo and again at the Japanese Chemical Society meeting in Nagoya at a red light (Figure 13). This is just one of many examples showing how our science community really is quite intertwined. The three months in Münster were over in a heartbeat and then it was time to leave for my biggest adventure yet: a one year postdoc- toral stay at the Tokyo Institute of Technology in Japan. (The attentive reader will have noticed my fondness for technical schools by now). The Land of the Rising Sun

So on April 13, 2013, I boarded a plane to Tokyo. Never in my life had I felt so unprepared for such an important life experi- ence. First of all my Japanese skills were barely existent. I could say a few basic phrases (as I found out during my stay “sumimasen”, “arigatou-gozaimasu” and “nihongo chotto” can be used to have almost a whole conversation), but reading and writing was absolutely out of the question for me. (Japanese is comprised of two alphabets known as Hiragana and Katakana and the Chinese Kanji.) Second of all, where Germans have a reputation for being blunt and sometimes brutally direct, Japa- nese people have a reputation for being very polite and would never ever directly voice any sort of criticism. Therefore, my biggest fear was to offend my lab mates or even worse my senseis, while not realizing when I was told when not to do something (the Japanese will not tell you NO, but when you ” chotto you should watch out). Another novelty for me was working in such a big group. The Suzuki-Ohmori laboratory was comprised of more than 35 people at the time of my start (Figure 14). On my ﬁrst day in the laboratory, I was afraid I would never be able to remember all the names and keep ﬁrst and last names straight. As a Westerner, it is often difﬁcult to recognize what is the ﬁrst and the last name of an Asian person. However Asian people have the same obstacle to overcome with Western names. Owing to my desk/bench partner Sunna Jung’s handy cheat sheet and descriptions, I was able to master this task surprisingly quickly. Again I realized early on that even though I could not speak the language, it was easy to pick up on the science—I guess having group meetings in Japanese speeded up the process a bit. But the chemistry was the ice-breaker that got the ball rolling and gave my lab mates the courage to start talking to me in English or try with very slow Japanese and many repetitions. Thanks to my desk/bench partner Sunna Jung (I kept teasing her that I was convinced that looking after me was part of her group job, and perhaps it was!), I also had the necessary support outside of the lab; going to the bank, post or getting a cell phone contract can be quite the challenge when one cannot read anything. I was very lucky to have found such an exceptional group of scientists who decided to take it upon themselves to give me the best possible life in Tokyo.

Restaurant visits were especially big adventures were Natto (fermented soybeans) and Motsunabe (soup with beef and pork guts, offal) were just some dishes with which my palate hori- zons were broadened (Figure 19). Another special thing was the amount of foreign scientists I met (most of them not chemists), due to my fellowship and Japanese class (Figure 20). We should keep in mind that some- times the most interesting ideas come from discussions with people who are not at home in our ﬁeld of expertise. Also it shows that chemistry cannot only bridge cultural differences, but is able to bring together different topics as one important linker. Now that my stay in Japan is coming to an end, I have to say good-bye to mentors and friends (Figure 21) that have inﬂuenced and shaped the way I see and do chemistry and a laboratory that has once again become my home. Luckily, I know from experience that some bonds cannot be broken and that I will see many of my friends and colleagues again in the future. As a matter of fact, I will be able to maintain the special relationship I have formed with the Suzuki-Ohmori laboratory. The interesting chemical problems I have stumbled upon while doing my research in Japan have led me to formulate a new research proposal bridging my PhD work and my postdoctoral work in one joint project. I am hoping that this might be the start of a new fruitful collaboration between a Japanese and German laboratory, with myself as the common link.

People often ask me about the differences I have experienced when it comes to how education or research is approached in Chem. Rec. 2014, 14, 709–725 © 2014 The Chemical Society of Japan and Wiley-VCH, Weinheim C h e m i s t r y w i t h o u t B o ( a ) r d e r s the various countries where I have studied. First of all, I think this is a very difﬁcult question to answer in a general way. For the most part, my experiences are based on working in one particular group at a time, so it is in no way a sociological study as would have been done by, perhaps, Robert K. Merton.[21,22] In my opinion, the “chemistry” between people in a group is the most important factor and the culture of a group depends very much on the group’s leader, that is, the professor. As for my experiences, I was always very lucky and able to work in the best, most supportive environment possible. While I ﬁnd that Germany, Switzerland and the United States have a very similar system for their laboratory organization—one pro- fessor, depending on the group size, one or more postdoctoral fellows, a lion’s share of PhD students and then some master and bachelor students—this is very different in Japan. As I mentioned before, a bigger group will have the head professor, an associate professor and one or more assistant professors. Postdoctoral fellows are rare and, depending on the group, there is a good chance that there are far more bachelor and master students than PhD students, which of course creates a very different working environment. I guess this hierarchical structure makes for a more formal way of conversation. Professors will always be addressed as sensei, older more experienced students are sempai, while people that are on your level will be called san and younger students might get the endearing name ending chan. This has a very different feel from the sometimes informal ways a western laboratory is run and where you might call your pro- fessor even by his or her ﬁrst name. Nevertheless, all professors are very approachable and always ready to teach and discuss science with the students.

One big difference I found was the amount of group jobs that are given in different laboratories. While in Germany, Switzerland and the United States there were technicians employed for looking after the NMR machines, to measure mass spectra, or to order certain chemicals or consumables, in Japan that was all done by the students themselves. Everyone has certain tasks, be it being in charge of the waste, ordering new solvents or servicing the NMR, which personally impressed me a lot. Also, something that I think would be impossible to do at a European or American university was the younger students raking leaves or shoveling snow in the winter on university grounds (Figure 22). One of the biggest differences I encountered was the space that was available for people to work. Unsurprisingly, due to the shortage of room in Japan, space is a big issue in a Japanese laboratory, so having your own fume hood is a luxury that is not always possible (Figure 23). Hence, sharing space and working cleanly and orderly in a small area is extraordinarily important in Japan. Of course, it is more convenient when spacious settings are provided like at MIT or ETH, but great science can be done in either layout. I think the sense of comradeship in a laboratory is always very high, since everyone is going through the same tough science school. However, in an especially small setting one has to be more aware about what everyone else is doing. It is essential to consult with one another and be considerate when using work space.

I guess the biggest difference can be found when com- paring the working hours. While in Germany and Switzer- land, about ten hours of work a day ﬁve days a week is average and Saturday is optional, in the United States and Japan six days a week are the norm and at least twelve hours a day of work. I think this discrepancy comes from a big cultural difference. In Japan, your life happens at work, this is where you meet your friends and socialize. In Germany and Switzerland, you also have friends in the laboratory, but the socializing happens more outside of work. So I think people just have a different approach to how they work during the time they are given. But for the most part a similar amount of work is achieved by all laboratories; I guess which system Fig. 19. I can say I could work with either model and I gen- erally achieved a similar amount of reactions. Undeniably working one more day a week will allow for more things to get done. Even though there are these undeniable distinctions, all laboratories I have worked in were ﬁlled with people that were passionate about their science and cared for their co-workers. The professors I had the pleasure of working for might have had different styles of leading their groups, but despite this fact all showed a great love for chemistry and a way of inspiring their students and supporting them in every possible way. In my opinion the important questions are not: “What country are you working in?” or “What are the set of rules that apply here?”; but “Have you found a group where the interpersonal chemistry is just right?” and “Will you approach your new work place with an open mind and a willingness to adapt to new things?” So far, I have been greeted with a warm welcome

personality, his curious nature and his love for chemistry, a truly inspiring person from whom we can all learn.[1–4, 23–29] Looking back, I wish I had heard about Prof. Nozoe’s tradition of autograph books before embarking on my scientiﬁc adven- tures. Collecting the autographs of the many people I met on the way would have been a wonderful reminder of this unique journey. But I guess it is more than ﬁtting that I will begin this new tradition here in Japan in the presence of a kindred spirit. Let’s see where the next part of my scientiﬁc adventures will take me and who will (re)cross my paths during this journey. Please sign my autograph book when we meet.
